\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Baryon acoustic oscillations are a signature of the early Universe imprinted
 in the distribution of galaxies and dark matter (DM) at the present epoch.
 As the early Universe expands and its temperature drops, sound waves propagatin
g in the baryon-photon plasma freeze into the matter distribution at decoupling.
 This leaves a characteristic peak in two-point correlation functions where
 the position of the peak is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim150{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 The BAO method utilizes this characteristic scale of the sound horizon
 as a standard ruler (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "1997PhRvL..79.3806T,1998ApJ...495...29G,1999MNRAS.304...75E"

\end_inset

).
 [
\color red
explain in more details in Intro
\color inherit
]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the primordial density fluctuation is linear and well understood,
 distribution of galaxies, which are biased tracers of the DM particles,
 suffers from non-linear growth of structure, redshift-space distortions,
 and galaxy biases.
 All those effects shift and broaden the BAO peak.
 The shift of the BAO peak causes a systematic bias on distance measurements,
 while the broadening degrades the measurements.
 There have been many studies quantifying those effects analytically [cite:xxx]
 and numerically [cite:xxx].
 Seo et al.
 investigated the effect of non-linear growth on BAO for the DM density
 field and found that the BAO peak is shifted by 0.3% at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=xxx$
\end_inset

 (in real-space, should I mention about redshift-space?).
 Mehta et al.
 found a larger but less than a percent shift for the case of galaxies,
 which is consistent with the analytic estimation done by Padmanabhan&White.
 While the shift of the BAO peak is less than a percent, the systematic
 error due to broadening is about xxx% for the case of xxx.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
In order to reduce the systematic errors on the masurements, Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eisenstein2007"

\end_inset

 proposed a method termed “reconstruction”.
 The assumption behind the method is that the non-linear growth at the scale
 of BAO mostly comes from the bulk flows.
 By modeling the bulk flows and shifting back positions of galaxies, the
 non-linearities in the density field is suppressed and the BAO peak is
 sharpened, as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bao_recon1"

\end_inset

.
 As a consequence, the reconstruction method corrects the shift to almost
 zero and reduces the systematic error by xxx%, which are verified both
 analytically [cite: xxx] and numerically [cite:xxx].
 Furthermore, this technique has been widely used in observational studies
 
\color inherit
(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "2007ApJ...664..660E,2009PhRvD..79f3523P,2009PhRvD..80l3501N"

\end_inset

)
\color black
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement t
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../../../Dropbox/Tomomi/Prospectus/bao_recon1.png
	lyxscale 40
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bao_recon1"

\end_inset

The one-dimensional correlation functions for DM with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 model at z=0.0 before (solid) and after reconstruction with 
\color red
smoothing scales
\color inherit
 of 5
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 (dotted) and 10
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 (short dashed).
 The long-dashed line shows the peak in the initial conditions.
 The figure is from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "2009PhRvD..80l3501N"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, we investigate how galaxy bias affects on the shift of the
 BAO peak before and after reconstruction.
 Because the shift in the BAO peak will cause the systematic bias for the
 inferred cosmological parameters, it is crucial to understand how much
 shift is caused by galaxy bias.
 A similar study is done by Ref.xxx at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

, but we are now testing the effect of galaxy bias at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

 (where the non-linear effects are more significant in galaxy samples) with
 a larger volume of simulations (
\color red
put quantitative number:xxx
\color inherit
) as well as a higher resolution (
\color red
xxx
\color inherit
).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[structure of the paper]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulations/Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
HACC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the HACC simulation [cite:xxx] in this work; HACC uses a hybrid parallel
 algorithmic structure, splitting the force calculation into a specially
 designed grid-based long/medium range spectral particle mesh (PM) component
 and a short-range solver, which uses direct particle-particle interactions,
 i.e., a P
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

M algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1988csup.book.....H"

\end_inset

.
 The simulation uses 
\begin_inset Formula $300$
\end_inset

 long time steps and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 subcycles.
 The choice of time steps is determined after several convergence tests
 such that the simulation reproduces an accurate halo mass functions as
 well as clusterings at the level of xxx% compared to full N-body simulations.
 Ref.
 X shows the details of those convergence tests; for example, the number
 of time steps is somewhat insensitive to reproduce the clustering of halos
 in real-space, but it is not in redshift-space.
 For the case of xxx time steps, the clustering in real-space agrees with
 the result from full N-body simulations up to xxxMpc/h, while the agreement
 in redshift-space is up to xxxMpc/h.
 The simulation assumes a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

CDM cosmology with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.2648$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.7352$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}h^{2}=0.02258$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{s}=0.963$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.71$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $4096^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a 
\begin_inset Formula $4h^{-1}{\rm Gpc}$
\end_inset

 box giving a particle mass of about 
\begin_inset Formula $5.3\times10^{10}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Dark matter halos are identified using the friends-of-friends (FOF) algorithm
 with the linking length of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.168$
\end_inset

.
 All of the results we consider here are at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 We have four realizations of the simulation and subdivide each of our 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times(4h^{-1}{\rm Gpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

 volumes into 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times16=64$
\end_inset

 subvolumes (
\begin_inset Formula $4(h^{-1}{\rm Gpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

 each) to estimate the covariance matrix for galaxy correlation functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[check force resolution and the meaning of the number of time steps]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Halo Occupation Distributions (HODs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
In order to test how galaxy biases affect to the BAO measurement, we generate
 galaxy mock catalogs with various galaxy biases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
To populate halos with galaxies, we use the Halo Occupation Distribution
 (HOD) method [e.g., xxx], w
\color inherit
hich assumes that the number of galaxies in a halo correlates with its halo
 mass.
 The HOD functional form (based on a number of free parameters, 5 in our
 case) provides probabilities for two types of galaxies: central and satellite
 galaxies.
 Central galaxies are the ones which exist at the center of the halo and
 often the most brigtest galaxies in its halo, while satellite galaxies
 are the ones which exists around the central galaxies.
 A halo hosts a central galaxy with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle N_{cen}(M)\rangle$
\end_inset

 and a number of satellite galaxies given by a Poisson distribution with
 mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle N_{sat}(M)\rangle$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle N_{cen}(M)\rangle=\frac{1}{2}{\rm erfc}\left[\frac{{\rm ln}(M_{cut}/M)}{\sqrt{2}\sigma}\right],\label{eq:Ncen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle N_{sat}(M)\rangle=N_{cen}(M)\left(\frac{M-\kappa M_{cut}}{M_{1}}\right)^{\alpha},\label{eq:Nsat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the halo mass, and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{cut}$
\end_inset

 is the characteristic minimum mass of halos which can host the central
 galaxy with the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the characteristic transition width, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 determines the minimum mass of halos for satellite galaxies, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 determines the fractional number of satellite galaxies.
 All those five parameters are free parameters.
 We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{sat}(M)$
\end_inset

 is zero when 
\begin_inset Formula $M<\kappa M_{cut}$
\end_inset

 and halos do not host satellite galaxies without a central galaxy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2005ApJ...633..791Z"

\end_inset

.
 The total number of galaxies hosted by each halo is a sum of the number
 of central and satellite galaxies.
 
\color red
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:weight_hod"

\end_inset

 illustrates 
\begin_inset Formula $<N_{cen}>$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $<N_{sat}>$
\end_inset

.

\color inherit
 Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Ncen"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Nsat"

\end_inset

 are not the only possible functional form for the HOD, but these forms
 are known to successfully reproduce the clustering of the BOSS galaxies
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2011ApJ...728..126W"

\end_inset

 and are therefore a convenient choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After assigning a number of galaxies to each halo, we distribute those galaxies
 within the halo.
 The central galaxy is always at the center of the halo, while the distribution
 of satellite galaxies follows a spherically symmetric NFW profile specified
 by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(r)=\frac{4\rho_{s}}{\frac{cr}{R_{{\rm vir}}}(1+\frac{cr}{R_{{\rm vir}}})^{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 is the virial radius for the halo, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the concentration parameter, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the density at the characteristic scale 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{s}=R_{{\rm vir}}/c$
\end_inset

.
 We use the emulator described in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013ApJ...768..123K"

\end_inset

 to generate a table of concentration-mass relations for halos at each redshift.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We set the velocity of the central galaxy to be equal to the host halo velocity.
 We assume that satellite galaxies are randomly moving inside the host halos.
 Therefore, the velocities of the satellite galaxies are the sum of their
 host halo velocity and a random virial component.
 For this random component, we draw from a Gaussian distribution with zero
 mean and variance given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle v_{x}^{2}\rangle=\langle v_{y}^{2}\rangle=\langle v_{z}^{2}\rangle=\frac{1}{3}\frac{GM}{R_{{\rm vir}}}.\label{eq:variance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been several discussions about velocity bias and how to assign/define
 the velocity for galaxies (e.g., using only inner 10% of particles to define
 velocities for central galaxies) [citation:xxx]; however, we expect that
 the velocities only affect on scales smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $30h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 in configuration-space, which is smaller than the scales on which we measure
 the BAO peak.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to construct samples of different galaxy biases, we construct realizati
ons of HOD models with the fixed parameters (
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{1}=14.0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1.013$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa=1.0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=0.85$
\end_inset

, which are used in Ref.
 xxx to fit to the galaxy clustering for DR11 [cite:xxx]), except for 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{cut}$
\end_inset

 which we vary from 12.5 to 14.1 in steps of 0.2.

\color red
 
\color black
The reason we only vary the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}$
\end_inset

 is because this parameter determines the mean halo mass which in turn primarily
 sets the galaxy bias.

\color inherit
 The resulting nine HODs span a range of biases from 1.5 to 3.0 corresponding
 to the number densities from xxx to xxx.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/old_ts485/Desktop/my_thesis/plots_BAO/hod_weight.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:weight_hod"

\end_inset

The expected number of galaxies 
\begin_inset Formula $<N_{g}>$
\end_inset

 as a function of halo mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M[h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}]$
\end_inset

 for the central galaxies (denoted as Ncen) and satellite galaxies (denoted
 as Nsat) with 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log_{10}}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.5$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the clustering of higher biased objects suffers from shot noise
 due to a random sampling of halos.
 In order to reduce the effect of shot noise on the BAO measurement, we
 give halos weights which are the expected number of galaxies, as shown
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:weight_hod"

\end_inset

.
 We call this method the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD method to differentiate with the regular HOD method.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:weight_hod"

\end_inset

 shows the expected number of central and satellite galaxies as a function
 of halo mass.
 While the expected numbers of central and satellite galaxies are treated
 as probabilities in the regular HOD method, the sum of the expected number
 of central and satellite galaxies is treated as weights in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD.
 In this way, the measurement of the BAO peak will not suffer from the variation
s due to subsampling.
 We compare the results from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and regular HOD methods in Sec.
 XXX and use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD samples for Sec.
 xxx.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[mention about the shot noise for the weighted case]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reconstruction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reconstruction method, originally proposed by Ref.xxx, partially removes
 the non-linear effect and sharpens the BAO peak.
 In this section, we briefly describe the steps and thier interpretation
 using Lagrangian pertubation theory (LPT).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In LPT, the position of a particle 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 is described as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{x}=\vec{q}+\vec{\Psi}(\vec{q}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}$
\end_inset

 is the initial position of the particle and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is the displacement vector field.
 The density field in configuration-space and Fourier-space are described
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(\vec{x})=(int)d^{3}q\delta^{(D)}(\vec{x}-\vec{q}-\vec{\Psi})-1\Leftrightarrow\delta(\vec{k})=(int)d^{3}qe^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}}-1).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evolution of the displacement field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 follows the Euler equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}\vec{\Psi}}{dt^{2}}+2H\frac{d\vec{\Psi}}{dt}=-\nabla_{x}\phi(\vec{x}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the gravitational potential.
 In first-order LPT, the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

, which is often called the Zel'dovich displacement, is given in Fourier-space
 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}(\vec{k})=i\frac{\vec{k}}{k^{2}}\delta_{0}(\vec{k}),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{0}(\vec{k})$
\end_inset

 is the linear density field.
 Then, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

displacement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{d}$
\end_inset

 is obtained by shifting back the position of the particle by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{d}(\vec{k})=(int)d^{3}qe^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{(\Psi}-\vec{\Psi}^{(1)})}-1),
\]

\end_inset

and compute the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shifted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

 using the random particles and moving their positions by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{s}(\vec{k})=(int)d^{3}qe^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}^{(1)}}-1).
\]

\end_inset

The reconstructed density field is obtained by 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{recon}=\delta_{d}-\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 In the linear regime, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{d}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}\rightarrow-\delta_{0}$
\end_inset

, and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{recon}\rightarrow\delta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we cannot use the linear density field to compute Zel'dovich
 displacement field.
 To estimate it, we simply smoothing the non-linear densty field to suppress
 the high-
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 modes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A basic algorithm is given below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Smooth the real-space density field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 to filter out high 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 modes with a Gaussian smoothing of scale 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S(k)={\rm e}^{-(kR)^{2}/2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute the Zel'dovich displacement field from linear perturbation theory:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\color{black}\vec{s}}(\vec{k})\equiv i\frac{\vec{k}}{k^{2}}S(k)\delta_{r}(\vec{k}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shift the particles by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{s}(\vec{k})$
\end_inset

 and recompute the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

displacement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field (denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{d}$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Generate randomly displaced particles and shift them by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}(\vec{k})$
\end_inset

.
 Compute the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shifted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field (denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute the reconstructed density field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}=\delta_{d}-\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the density field is in redshift-space, we recover the real-space density
 field by simply estimating linear velocity field and shifting back the
 position of the particle along the line-of-sight.
 A basic algorithm is given below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Take a redshift-space density field and divide it by 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+\beta\mu^{2})$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1987MNRAS.227....1K"

\end_inset

) to obtain real-space density approximated from linear perturbation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}(\vec{k})=\frac{\delta_{s}}{1+\beta\mu},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=f/b$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f\approx\Omega_{m}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the galaxy bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Smooth 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}$
\end_inset

 to filter out high 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 modes with a Gaussian smoothing of scale 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S(k)$
\end_inset

, to eliminate the effect of small-scale, non-linear structure of the density
 field:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S(k)={\rm e}^{-(kR)^{2}/2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute the velocity field from linear perturbation theory:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla\cdot\vec{v}_{{\rm lin}}=-f\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}(\vec{x)}\Longleftrightarrow\vec{v}_{{\rm lin}}(\vec{k})=\frac{i\vec{k}f}{k^{2}}\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}(\vec{k}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shift the particles in redshift-space by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{v}_{{\rm lin}}/H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and compute the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reconstructed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{{\rm recon}}(\vec{k})=(int)d^{3}q{\rm e}^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}({\rm e}^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi s}(\vec{q})+ik_{z}v_{z,{\rm lin}}/H_{o}}-1)
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}_{s}(\vec{q})=\vec{\Psi}(\vec{q})+\frac{v_{z,{\rm NL}}}{H_{o}}\hat{z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we take advantage of periodicity of the simulations to perform
 all of these steps using fast Fourier transforms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to compute correlation functions, we use the Landy-Szalay estimator
 [cite:xxx]:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi(r)=\frac{DD(r)-2DR(r)+RR(r)}{RR(r)},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $DD$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $DR$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $RR$
\end_inset

 are the number of galaxy-galaxy, galaxy-random, random-random pairs separated
 by distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 For randomly distributed particles, we use about ten times of the number
 of galaxies.We bin our correlation functions in 
\begin_inset Formula $4h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 bins starting from 
\begin_inset Formula $2h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $198h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the case of the reconstructed galaxy samples, the equivalent Landy-Szalay
 estimator becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\xi(r)=\frac{DD(r)-2DS(r)+SS(r)}{RR(r)},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 represents the distribution of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

displacement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the distribution of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shifted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field.
 The derivation of the above estimator is following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\xi(r) & = & <(\delta_{d}-\delta_{s})(\delta_{d}-\delta_{s})>\\
 & = & <\delta_{d}\delta_{d}>-2<\delta_{d}\delta_{s}>+<\delta_{s}\delta_{s}>\\
 & = & \frac{DD-2DR+RR}{RR}-2\frac{DS-DR-SR+RR}{RR}+\frac{SS-2SR+RR}{RR}\\
 & = & \frac{DD-2DS+SS}{RR}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fitting Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to fit the BAO peak, we construct models of correlation functions
 with fiducial cosmology.
 For the case of isotropic BAO measurements (i.e., spherically-averaged clustering
 statistics), we use the monopole term of the correlation functions and
 measure how much the BAO peak is shifted with respect to fiducial cosmology.
 For the case of anisotropic measurements, we utilize the Alcock-Pezinski
 efect, which distort the BAO peak measured through the Hubble distance
 and the angular diameter distance differently and generates anisotropy
 when the true cosmology is different from the fiducial cosmology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Isotropic BAO measurements 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:fit_isotropic"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We measure the BAO scale using the methodology in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013arXiv1303.4666A"

\end_inset

.
 Specifically, we describe the observed correlation function by 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{{\rm fit}}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xi_{{\rm fit}}(r)=B\xi_{t}(\alpha r)+A_{0}+A_{1}/r+A_{2}/r^{2},\label{eq:model1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a template correlation function, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the galaxy bias squared and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0,1,2}$
\end_inset

 
\color red
remove broadband mismatches in our templates
\color inherit
 (not sure what it means...).
 The template correlation function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{t}(r)$
\end_inset

 is given by a Fourier transform of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}(k)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{t}(r)=(P_{{\rm lin}}(k)-P_{nw}(k))e^{-\frac{k^{2}\Sigma^{2}}{2}}+P_{nw}(k),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{{\rm lin}}(k)$
\end_inset

 is the linear power spectrum and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{nw}(k)$
\end_inset

 is the no-wiggle power spectrum described in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1998ApJ...496..605E"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is a nonlinear parameter that accounts for the broadening of the BAO peak
 due to nonlinear evolution.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=7h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 for pre-reconstruction and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=0h{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 for post-reconstruction, and we will discuss the reason for those choices
 in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:smoothing"

\end_inset

.
 We determine the parameters by minimizing 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}=(\xi_{{\rm HOD}}-\xi_{{\rm fit}})^{{\rm T}}C^{-1}(\xi_{{\rm HOD}}-\xi_{{\rm fit}})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse covariance matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{{\rm HOD}}$
\end_inset

 is a correlation function which 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{{\rm fit}}$
\end_inset

 is fitted to.
 We consider the measured correlation function from 
\begin_inset Formula $60h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $160h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 in bins of 
\begin_inset Formula $4h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 for a total of 25 data points.
 Since all the parameters except 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are linear parameters, we can compute the best fit values for those parameters
 analytically; however, we perform the minimization on a grid of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values and the bias parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with a Gaussian prior to avoid the negative values for the bias parameter.
 We give a Gaussian prior on bias parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that we measure linear galaxy bias 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 between the template correlation function and data on 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in[40h^{-1}{\rm Mpc},50h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}]$
\end_inset

 and give a prior to 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}\sim1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $B=b^{2}B_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measures the shift of the BAO peak from its original position predicted
 by linear perturbation theory.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

 implies that there is no shift of the BAO peak.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 measures the shift in the BAO scale relative to what is assumed for the
 template function, and is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha\equiv\left(\frac{D_{{\rm V}}(z)}{r_{{\rm d}}}\right)\left(\frac{r_{{\rm d,fid}}}{D_{{\rm V}}^{{\rm fid}}(z)}\right),\label{eq:alpha_ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{{\rm d}}$
\end_inset

 is the sound horizon 
\color red
at the drag epoch (i.e., the time at which the baryons are released from the
 Compton drag of the photons)
\color inherit
 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{{\rm V}}\equiv\left[cz(1+z)^{2}D_{{\rm A}}(z)^{2}H^{-1}(z)\right]^{1/3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{{\rm A}}$
\end_inset

 being the angular diameter distance and 
\begin_inset Formula $H(z)$
\end_inset

, the Hubble parameter.
 In the absence of systematics, we expect 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

; deviations from this represent a systematic bias to the inferred distance-reds
hift relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Is drag epoch and decoupling the same?]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[the reason the redshift-evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{d}$
\end_inset

 is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $1/D_{V}$
\end_inset

 ]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Anisotropic 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:fit_anisotropic"

\end_inset


\end_layout

