\begin_layout Section
Results for Isotropic BAO: Real-Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we show the results of the isotropic BAO analysis with
 and without reconstruction (i.e., measuring the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values from the real-space correlation functions) using the method discussed
 in Sec.
 xxx.
 Here, we use the samples generated from the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD method in order to remove the variance on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values due to randomly subsampling halos, which is particularly large for
 the samples with high biases.
 We discuss the effect of subsampling and compare the results between the
 regular HOD and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD methods in Sec.
 xxx.
 In Sec.
 xxx, we show how the smoothing scale affects the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values we measure.
 In the last two sections, we show the results of the effect of galaxy bias
 on the BAO measurements without and with reconstruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparison between weighted and regular HOD methods
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:weightHOD"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we compare the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values measured through the samples using the regular and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD methods to show how the shot noise affects the measurements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:variation_hod"

\end_inset

 shows the comparison between the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values measured from the regular HOD and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD samples.
 For the case of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weighted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 HOD method, we first compute the correlation functions with the given weights
 and measure the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values for the 64 samples denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{{\rm weighted}}$
\end_inset

.
 For the regular HOD samples, we generate three different realizations (in
 total of 192 samples) for 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log_{10}}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.5$
\end_inset

 and five (or six?) realizations (in total of 320 samples) for 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=14.1$
\end_inset

, and measure the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{HOD}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we compare the differences in the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values between 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{{\rm weighted}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{HOD}$
\end_inset

.
 For both cases, the mean of the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $<\alpha_{HOD}-\alpha_{{\rm weighted}}>$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm0.02\%$
\end_inset

; the error of the mean for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.5$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.45\%$
\end_inset

, while it is 
\begin_inset Formula $2.44\%$
\end_inset

 for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm log}_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=14.1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

