\begin_layout Subsection
Effects of Smoothing Scales
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:smoothing"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[ask about eq.
 7 in Noh et al...
 how 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 is related to the smoothing scales...]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we discuss how the smoothing parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 in the template correlation function affects the measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 The expected value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is xxx, which is computed from xxx.
 We use the sample with 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{10}M_{{\rm cut}}=12.5$
\end_inset

.
 For each set of samples (
\begin_inset Formula $4(h^{-1}{\rm Gpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

 each and 64 samples in total), we change the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and measure the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sigma_prerecon"

\end_inset

 shows the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 values as a function of various values for the smoothing parameter in real-spac
e before reconstruction.
 While decreasing the smoothing scale makes the shift of the BAO peak smaller
 monotonically, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 values indicate that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=7h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 gives the smallest value and therefore the best fit.
 We repeat the same exercises for different HOD samples (i.e., different galaxy
 biases) and for the case of post-reconstruction.
 For the case of samples with various HOD parameters, we did not see any
 bias-dependence on the smoothing scales.
 For the case of post-reconstruction, the smoothing scale which gives the
 smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 value is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma=0h{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, which is much smaller than what we expected.
