\begin_layout Subsection
Effects of Biased Tracers on BAO Peaks in Real-Space before Reconstruction
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:real-prerecon"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*give a table of HOD pareameters and bias values (compare pre/post-reconstructio
n)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate the effect of galaxy bias on the measurement
 of the BAO peak for the samples without reconstruction in real-space.
 We use the method described in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:fit_isotropic"

\end_inset

 to measure the shift of the BAO peak.
 It is crucial to understand how much shift is caused by galaxy bias, because
 the shift due to the deviation from the fiducial cosmology and the shift
 due to galaxy bias is indistinguishable and can be a systematic bias in
 cosmological measurements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:alpha_prerecon"

\end_inset

 shows the measured shifts in the BAO scale as a function of galaxy bias,
 for the nine HODs described above.
 We detect the shift in the BAO scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim3\sigma$
\end_inset

 for most samples) but do not detect a strong variation with the galaxy
 bias.
 Indeed, the shift is consistent with being constant for biases 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

 2.5 and only increases for extremely large biases.
 These results agree with the trends shown in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2011ApJ...734...94M"

\end_inset

, although note that the absolute values of the shifts differ since Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2011ApJ...734...94M"

\end_inset

 considers samples at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

, while the results here are at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*[estimate the expected trend for redshift evolution of the shift from Padmanabh
an & White] We also find that our results are roughly consistent with expectatio
ns from perturbation theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2008PhRvD..77b3533C,2009PhRvD..80f3508P,2012PhRvD..85j3523S"

\end_inset

, although we find a weaker mass dependence than what was predicted in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2009PhRvD..80f3508P"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*the increase of the mean and std of alpha as a function of bias: is it
 consistent with the prediction from Padmanabhan&White?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*the scatter consistent with prediction from shot noise?
\end_layout

